In the quest for reducing CO2 emissions, cutting energy losses has received major attention in the past decade. Despite various efforts to make industrial and power generating processes more efficient, 50–80% of the primary energy is dissipated as waste heat, where low-grade waste heat (up to 100 °C) forms the largest contribution1. Forman et al.estimated that in 2012 around 43 PWh (1.6 × 1020 J) of low-grade waste heat was emitted globally1. Although not all waste heat can be converted into power due to the conservation of entropy, the Carnot efficiency (1-ThotTcold\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
